3 Assigning variables from lines of output

Look at the file inputs/sample_list.txt. This has information that we would typically like to use to create read group information while aligning sequences.

Here is a script that will pick out a line with index i from that file and print it to stdout:

# this just says which line/index to get
i=3; 

# this is the awk one-liner that picks it out and prints it
awk -v L=$i '$1==L {print; exit}' inputs/sample_list.txt

Try running the above to see what it does and how it works. Then…

3.1 Capture the output of the above into an array variable called SAMPARRAY

3.2 Now, pick out the appropriate elements of SAMPARRAY into five new variables: SAMPLE, LIBRARY, FLOWCELL, FQ1, and FQ2. Print those new variables, using echo. Show your code and output in the following block.

Here is another approach :

Another way that those five variables above could be set, is to make a command line directly in awk and then evaluate it in bash. For example:

awk -v L=$i '$1==L {print "SAMPLE=" $2 "; LIBRARY=" $3 "; FLOWCELL=" $4 "; FQ1=" $5 "; FQ2=" $6; exit}' inputs/sample_list.txt

3.3 Write a block of code that evalautes the above, puts the result on the command line and then properly executes the variable assignments implied in the output. Remember the eval keyword.

3.4 Which approach do you find cleaner and easier to read?

5 Tests and combinations of exit statuses

The test function tests statements (or expressions) and then returns SUCCESS if the statement is true and NO_SUCCESS otherwise. A shorthand for the test function is a pair of square brackets, like this:

[ expression ]

Read the manual page (man test) to see what kinds of tests are possible.

5.1 Assign the value ./inputs/sample_list.txt to FILE

Now, [ -f $FILE ] returns SUCCESS if $FILE exists and is a regular file.

5.2 Use [ -f $FILE ] and the && to make a command line that prints “Yes, the file, $FILE, exists” if the file does exit and is a regular file. Show it in action on FILE

5.3 Use || to print “No, $FILE does not exist” when it does not. First run it while FILE=./inputs/sample_list.txt, then set FILE to a path that does not exist

That is all well and good, but it would be nice to have a single series of statements that would print the affirmative (“Yes, the file, $FILE, exists”) when true, and also the negative (“No, $FILE does not exist”) when true…

5.4 Use if/then/else/fi to test for the existence of $FILE and then print the appropriate response if it exists or not

6.13 Hard problem:

There is a script in scripts called random-fail.sh. It prints the number of digits in the first column of the first row of a file. I want you to cycle over the files in all_fastqs, redirecting stderr to append to a single file called error-messages.txt (this file should be removed before you start cycling over the FASTQS) and also redirecting standard output from random-fail.sh into a file that has the same name as the one from all_fastqs1 but with .gz replaced by .counts. That is when you run the script like:

./scripts/random-fail.sh all_fastqs/s18N03747_USPD16103199-N704-AK400_H3LJCCCX2_L4_2.fq

I want the output to go into a file called:

all_fastqs/s18N03747_USPD16103199-N704-AK400_H3LJCCCX2_L4_2.counts

After that, cat the contents of the .counts file, but only if the random-fail.sh script did not fail on that particular file. (random_fail.sh fails some fraction of the time, randomly, and when it does it returns a non-zero exit status).

So, at the end, you should have a lot of files like:

all_fastqs/s18N03747_USPD16103199-N704-AK400_H3LJCCCX2_L4_2.counts

and you should have a file, error-messages.txt, that contains all the messages written to stderr each time random-fail.sh failed. Also, you should never have tried to cat a .counts file that did not exist.
